        contents_html_en: `<img src="../blog-image-14.png" alt="Soybean Sprout Soup" class="blog-post-image"><h2>Soybean Sprout Soup - Nutty and Nourishing Comfort in a Bowl</h2><p>Soybean sprouts are packed with nutrients, though they may feel unfamiliar to some. So why not turn them into a warm, gentle soup? This nutty, wholesome broth is comforting, nourishing, and just right for soothing the body from the inside out.</p><h3>ğŸ›’ Ingredients (Serves 2â€“3)</h3><ul><li>Soybean sprouts â€“ 200g</li><li>Water â€“ 5 cups</li><li>Soup soy sauce â€“ 1 tbsp</li><li>Minced garlic â€“ 1 tsp</li><li>Scallion â€“ Â½ stalk</li><li>Salt â€“ to taste</li><li>Dried anchovies or kelp (for broth, optional)</li><li>Korean chili flakes or chopped chili pepper (optional, for heat)</li></ul><h3>ğŸ”ª Preparation</h3><p>Rinse soybean sprouts thoroughly and trim the heads and roots â†’ Removing roots gives a cleaner taste, but note: much of the nutrition is concentrated in the roots So if youâ€™re focused on health, itâ€™s fine to leave them on.</p><p>Slice scallion thinly, and mince the garlic.</p><p>If using broth: boil dried anchovies and kelp in cold water for 10â€“15 minutes, then strain.</p><h3>ğŸ³ Cooking Method</h3><ol><li>In a pot, add water or prepared broth and bring to a boil.</li><li>Once boiling, add the cleaned soybean sprouts and cook over medium heat for 3â€“5 minutes â†’ Be sure to add sprouts either before boiling or after boiling begins, but not bothâ€”this prevents unwanted odors.</li><li>Add garlic and soup soy sauce to season â†’ Soup soy sauce is different from regular soy sauce; it gives a deeper yet clearer flavor tailored for Korean soups.</li><li>Once sprouts start turning translucent, add scallion and simmer for 1â€“2 more minutes.</li><li>If you prefer heat, stir in Korean chili flakes or fresh chopped chili pepper.</li><li>Taste and finish by adjusting salt to your liking.</li></ol><h3>ğŸ’¡ Tips</h3><ul><li>No broth? No problem! Clean water alone can produce a refreshingly light soup.</li><li>Store leftovers in the fridge and enjoy chilled as a cold soupâ€”itâ€™s delicious that way too.</li><li>Feeling under the weather? Add extra garlic and spicy chili to clear your head and warm you up.</li><li>For extra aroma, try using thin chives instead of scallions.</li></ul><p>One handful of sprouts, a whole pot of warmth and wellness.</p>`
