        contents_html_en: `<img src="../blog-image-17.png" alt="Chicken Karaage" class="blog-post-image"><h2>Chicken Karaage â€“ The Clean Elegance of Japanese Fried Chicken</h2><p>Looking for chicken with clean and deep flavor? This classic Japanese fried dish features thin, crispy coating that holds juicy, tender meat inside. Though deep-fried, itâ€™s far from greasyâ€”light on the tongue and refined in taste. Letâ€™s make chicken karaage together.</p><h3>ğŸ›’ Ingredients (Serves 2â€“3)</h3><ul><li>Boneless chicken thighs â€“ 400g</li><li>Soy sauce â€“ 2 tbsp</li><li>Cooking sake â€“ 2 tbsp</li><li>Minced ginger â€“ 1 tsp</li><li>Minced garlic â€“ 1 tsp</li><li>Salt & pepper â€“ to taste</li><li>Potato starch or potato starch + flour mix â€“ Â½ cup</li><li>Neutral oil for frying â€“ appropriate amount</li><li>Lemon wedges (optional)</li><li>Mayo or tartar sauce (optional)</li></ul><h3>ğŸ”ª Preparation</h3><p>Cut the chicken into 3â€“4cm pieces â†’ If too small, the juices may evaporate while frying; too large, and it may not cook through properly.</p><p>Pat dry with paper towels.</p><p>Marinate with soy sauce, sake, ginger, garlic, salt, and pepper for 15â€“20 minutes â†’ Marinating longer (e.g., 30+ min) is fine, but may intensify the alcohol aroma from sake.</p><p>Before frying, gently blot excess moisture and coat each piece evenly with starch mixture.</p><h3>ğŸ³ Cooking Method</h3><ol><li>In a deep pan, pour plenty of oil and preheat over medium heat.</li><li>Test the temperature: drop in a pinch of starchâ€”if it bubbles immediately and floats, itâ€™s around 160â€“170Â°C (320â€“340Â°F).</li><li>Add chicken pieces and fry for 2â€“3 minutes until lightly golden, then remove and let sit briefly to drain oil and cool slightly.</li><li>Return to the oil for a second fry, about 1â€“2 minutes, to build extra crispiness.</li><li>Drain well and serve with lemon wedges or dipping sauce of your choice.</li></ol><h3>âš ï¸ Caution While Cooking</h3><p>Make sure to remove moisture thoroughly before frying to avoid oil splatter.</p><p>Keep oil at the proper temperatureâ€”too low makes it soggy, too high burns the outside before the inside cooks.</p><p>After frying, set chicken on paper towels briefly to remove excess oil and preserve crisp texture.</p><h3>ğŸ’¡ Tips</h3><ul><li>Replace ginger with yuzu syrup for a light citrusy twist.</li><li>A 7:3 ratio of potato starch to flour creates perfect crunch outside and tenderness inside.</li><li>Pair with beer, oolong tea, or a mocktail to recreate a cozy izakaya vibe at home.</li></ul><p>Crisp yet refinedâ€”karaage breaks the stereotype of greasy fried food.</p>`
